## Acceptance Criteria

### API Routes
1. `GET /api/projects` returns all projects with their latest deployment status.
2. `POST /api/projects` creates a project, validates with `createProjectSchema`, generates a slug, returns the created project.
3. `GET /api/projects/:id` returns full project details including latest deployment info.
4. `PATCH /api/projects/:id` updates allowed fields, validates with `updateProjectSchema`.
5. `DELETE /api/projects/:id` removes the project and all associated data (cascade).
6. `GET /api/projects/:id/deployments` returns paginated deployments sorted by `created_at DESC`.
7. `POST /api/projects/:id/deployments` creates a deployment record with status `queued` and enqueues a build.
8. `GET /api/projects/:id/deployments/:did` returns deployment detail with build log S3 URL.
9. `GET /api/projects/:id/env?scope=production` returns env vars for the specified scope with secret values masked as `"***"`.
10. `POST /api/projects/:id/env` creates an env var, encrypting the value if `isSecret` is true.
11. `PATCH /api/projects/:id/env/:varId` updates an env var (value and/or isSecret flag).
12. `DELETE /api/projects/:id/env/:varId` deletes an env var.
13. All routes return 401 for unauthenticated requests (via `withAuth`).
14. All routes return 400 for invalid input with descriptive Zod error messages.
15. All routes return 404 when the referenced project or resource does not exist.

### Webhook Handler
16. Push events to the production branch create a deployment record and enqueue a build.
17. Push events to non-production branches are ignored (200 response, no side effects).
18. Duplicate delivery IDs are detected and return 200 without re-processing.
19. Pull request events are acknowledged but routed to a placeholder handler (Phase 7).
20. Installation events are logged and handled.
21. Invalid signatures return 401 (already implemented).

### UI Pages
22. The projects list page displays all projects in a responsive grid with status badges.
23. Clicking a project card navigates to the project detail page.
24. The "Connect Repo" button initiates the GitHub App installation flow.
25. The project detail page shows production URL, recent deployments, and working tab navigation.
26. The deployments page shows deployment history with status, commit SHA, branch, and timestamps.
27. The deployment detail page renders build logs with ANSI color support.
28. The environment variables page allows full CRUD with scope toggle and secret masking.
29. Bulk edit mode parses pasted KEY=VALUE lines and creates env vars.

